H (and likewise other reoccurring parts of the documentation like README). And _this_ seems like a bigger issue and may even turn out to be unsolvable at the moment as this stuff seems to be technology- and even target-group-specific.","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1613646043,"nonce":"FBgme66qb6UvUSSbeTAfjJEsMIQ=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlRWRpdDo0OTU2MjM4MzY="},"target":"51cad8569def26c2b25cc150d905ad6b6c7efd71e84fb5127d4dfd34172f5638","message":"The sBoM concept brings several disadvantages while advantages are not prevailing at the moment, plus it's not technically necessary anymore.\n\n**Disadvantages:**\n\n- building the sBoM takes a significant effort in the metadata creation (← manual work)\n- the sBoM template is not standardised outside this repository\n- the sBoM structure lacks some functions due to its simplistic approach (e.g. various columns for specific part referencing (e.g. electronic components) as suggested in #16) and has some ambiguity in it (e.g. position number \u0026 unit count for subassemblies in the sBoM ← indeed an issue that is still open even in official BoM standards)\n\n**Advantages:**\n\n- BUY and STD parts become accessible to the graph database and can hence be analysed \u0026 combined with other data (what we don't do at the moment)\n- simple overview of all parts directly visible for the user when searching MOSHes; specifically useful when comparing MOSHes\n\n---\n\nThere are dozens of standards for BoMs and I'm not seeing the benefit anymore of exposing a new, not well-tested approach to world. To follow our metadata specification, people are forced to either adopt to the sBoM template in regards of their own BoM or to produce redundant information in case they already have a BoM.\n\n---\n\n**Suggested solution:**\n\nThe important part is that all relevant information is accessible. \n\n- This can be done in MOSH \u0026 POSH files.\n- A MOSH file contains then \n  - URL to the BoM\n  - URLs to POSH files\n  - URLs to MOSH releases/snapshots \n- POSH files remain unchanged\n\nOpen question: When MOSHes that follow this metadata specifications are referring to each other (MOSH A v1.0 uses MOSH B v1.2) → is version-specific linking possible just based on the given URL which may be either a release or a commit?\\\nI assume yes, but it would require some extra effort (= system can be upgraded later)\\\nIf we could only link to the versionless MOSH (was called TOSH in some issue), this would already be from great value. Which specific version was used or which specific BUY parts are in there are all relevant and good, but not crucial questions. We still don't know if people actually need this detailed level of information in a graph database. And if it turns out that they need it → this would be a great outcome of a research project and we can upgrade the system for a reason.\n\nNext step (after OPEN!NEXT, I presume) would be to standardise BoMs for OSH (and likewise other reoccurring parts of the documentation like README). And _this_ seems like a bigger issue and may even turn out to be unsolvable at the moment as this stuff seems to be technology- and even target-group-specific.","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1613646282,"nonce":"YqwPVVAA7McXHSgvMoN1q4CP+aA=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdElzc3VlRWRpdDo0OTU2MjU3MzM="},"target":"51cad8569def26c2b25cc150d905ad6b6c7efd71e84fb5127d4dfd34172f5638","message":"The sBoM concept brings several disadvantages while advantages are not prevailing at the moment, plus it's not technically necessary anymore.\n\n**Disadvantages:**\n\n- building the sBoM takes a significant effort in the metadata creation (← manual work)\n- the sBoM template is not standardised outside this repository\n- the sBoM structure lacks some functions due to its simplistic approach (e.g. various columns for specific part referencing (e.g. electronic components) as suggested in #16) and has some ambiguity in it (e.g. position number \u0026 unit count for subassemblies in the sBoM ← indeed an issue that is still open even in official BoM standards)\n\n**Advantages:**\n\n- BUY and STD parts become accessible to the graph database and can hence be analysed \u0026 combined with other data (what we don't do at the moment)\n- simple overview of all parts directly visible for the user when searching MOSHes; specifically useful when comparing MOSHes\n\n---\n\nThere are dozens of standards for BoMs and I'm not seeing the benefit anymore of exposing a new, not well-tested approach to world. To follow our metadata specification, people are forced to either adopt to the sBoM template in regards of their own BoM or to produce redundant information in case they already have a BoM.\n\n---\n\n**Suggested solution:**\n\nThe important part is that all relevant information is accessible. \n\n- This can be done in MOSH \u0026 POSH files.\n- A MOSH file contains then \n  - URL to the BoM\n  - URLs to POSH files\n  - URLs to MOSH releases/snapshots \n  - rest remains unchanged\n- POSH files remain unchanged\n\nOpen question: When MOSHes that follow this metadata specifications are referring to each other (MOSH A v1.0 uses MOSH B v1.2) → is version-specific linking possible just based on the given URL which may be either a release or a commit?\\\nI assume yes, but it would require some extra effort (= system can be upgraded later)\\\nIf we could only link to the versionless MOSH (was called TOSH in some issue), this would already be from great value. Which specific version was used or which specific BUY parts are in there are all relevant and good, but not crucial questions. We still don't know if people actually need this detailed level of information in a graph database. And if it turns out that they need it → this would be a great outcome of a research project and we can upgrade the system for a reason.\n\nNext step (after OPEN!NEXT, I presume) would be to standardise BoMs for OSH (and likewise other reoccurring parts of the documentation like README). And _this_ seems like a bigger issue and may even turn out to be unsolvable at the moment as this stuff seems to be technology- and even target-group-specific.","files":null}]}